Lea is the best place in the world!!! I have been there so many times over the years, and I have to say that they have actually gotten better ever since Covid arrived. Lea has done an amazing job of transforming from a sit-down neighborhood Italian place, into a multifaceted food and beverage market, coffee shop, bakery, and specialty store, while still maintaining a neighborhood vibe. I've been working from home since March, and the highlights of each day are when I travel to Lea multiple times for coffee, soup, pasta, and every so often...An egg sandwich. For thanksgiving this year, we ordered the Thanksgiving takeout package, and it was excellent...Everything was delicious, and it was just the right amount...I hate having leftovers for weeks on end. Today, I picked up the "Big Nosh" platter for Hanukkah, and it all looks really good. I am looking forward to munching on this stuff later today. If you live in the hood(and even if you do not), I recommend going to Lea, it will be worth your while.

When there is a problem, you apologize, fix it and more on. Sadly that's not what happened here recently. We've been going to Lea for about a year and absolutely love the wait staff who are friendly and make you feel at home. However the other night, my wife found what appeared to be a piece of glass in her pasta.  We politely showed it to the waitress who apologized profusely and brought it to the manager--who turned out to the owner. After about 5 minutes, he come out to explain that it was not glass but a particularly sharp piece of salt. So be it.  Whether salt or glass, it caused pain when my wife bit into it. The proper response would've been to make up for the issue--regardless of the cause.  Instead after another extended period of time, they asked if she would like another dish and when the manager/owner left he made a joke about it. When the bill came there was no consideration. How much would have been gained by comping the dish or offering a free glass of wine. Instead, they lost two loyal customers. #Restaurant101fail

Definitely a fan. Also depending on my mood.  I love Lea's because they have a very limited menu. I get flustered when there is too much to choose from.  The first time we went there, I went with with my husband. It was wonderful. We ordered Iced Coffee, Cortelyou Mezze which consists of A platter of small plates including eggs any style, roasted potato, eggplant, fennel salad, grated cherry tomatoes and toast and the Challa French Toast. Everything was absolutely phenomenal. From taste to texture - pure perfection.  Service was great too, we didn't wait for a table nor did we have to wait to be served. The wait staff are always on their toes ready to help. We did call a few weeks later to get some take out and were truly disappointed. They packed the food in brown paper boxes, so by the time it came home to us it was an absolute mess. (So never again). But I think they have since implemented that they will not deliver certain dishes. And I agree with that.  A couple of days ago I went for lunch with a friend. We ordered some coffee, Grilled Polenta & Eggs which are Soaked in tomato sauce, topped with two sunny-side eggs and grated pecorino cheese and Rigatoni - Tomato sauce, mozzarella cheese, basil and Parmesan cheese.  Aside for the Rigatoni being a little under cooked (Hard, chewy and definitely not Al dente) everything else was great. The spices in the tomato sauce were superb. Spicy and peppery tinge to the finish). The Grilled Polenta was also tasty, perfectly cooked eggs on top.  Overall - I definitely recommend Leas as a Brunch/Lunch spot. I have yet to try them for dinner although I don't think they would disappoint.
